</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[125,1172,1629,1685]" lastBlockId="5.[138,1185,1023,1111]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="2705" pageId="4" pageNumber="2704">
Arista long, plumose (
<figureCitation box="[397,495,1629,1653]" captionStart="Figures 8–11" captionStartId="5.[138,207,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[142,1182,137,871]" captionTargetId="figure-146@5.[138,1186,133,875]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 8–11. Cacoxenus (Nankangomyia) unipaxillus sp. nov., „. (8) Antenna. (9) Epandrium, cercus, and surstylus, lateral view. (10, 11) Hypandrium (hypd), gonopod (gon), parameres (pm), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a), ventral and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233486/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="2704">Figure 8</figureCitation>
); cercus protruded on posteroventral corner (
<figureCitation box="[1057,1156,1629,1653]" captionStart="Figures 8–11" captionStartId="5.[138,207,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[142,1182,137,871]" captionTargetId="figure-146@5.[138,1186,133,875]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 8–11. Cacoxenus (Nankangomyia) unipaxillus sp. nov., „. (8) Antenna. (9) Epandrium, cercus, and surstylus, lateral view. (10, 11) Hypandrium (hypd), gonopod (gon), parameres (pm), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a), ventral and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233486/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="2704">Figure 9</figureCitation>
); surstylus with a distinct, apically pointed, peg-like prensiseta (
<figureCitation box="[845,944,1661,1685]" captionStart="Figures 8–11" captionStartId="5.[138,207,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[142,1182,137,871]" captionTargetId="figure-146@5.[138,1186,133,875]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 8–11. Cacoxenus (Nankangomyia) unipaxillus sp. nov., „. (8) Antenna. (9) Epandrium, cercus, and surstylus, lateral view. (10, 11) Hypandrium (hypd), gonopod (gon), parameres (pm), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a), ventral and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233486/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="2704">Figure 9</figureCitation>
); paramere apically with a small, incised notch (
<figureCitation box="[480,594,1023,1047]" captionStart="Figures 8–11" captionStartId="5.[138,207,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[142,1182,137,871]" captionTargetId="figure-146@5.[138,1186,133,875]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 8–11. Cacoxenus (Nankangomyia) unipaxillus sp. nov., „. (8) Antenna. (9) Epandrium, cercus, and surstylus, lateral view. (10, 11) Hypandrium (hypd), gonopod (gon), parameres (pm), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a), ventral and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233486/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Figure 11</figureCitation>
); aedeagus thick, dorsally membranous, ventrally sclerotized, basally slightly pubescent, apically with a small, triangular projection (
<figureCitation box="[146,317,1087,1111]" captionStart="Figures 8–11" captionStartId="5.[138,207,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[142,1182,137,871]" captionTargetId="figure-146@5.[138,1186,133,875]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 8–11. Cacoxenus (Nankangomyia) unipaxillus sp. nov., „. (8) Antenna. (9) Epandrium, cercus, and surstylus, lateral view. (10, 11) Hypandrium (hypd), gonopod (gon), parameres (pm), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a), ventral and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233486/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Figures 10, 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
