<paragraph blockId="5.[138,259,1167,1191]" box="[138,259,1167,1191]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">
<emphasis box="[138,259,1167,1191]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[138,1185,1215,1239]" box="[138,1185,1215,1239]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">
Some characters commonly seen in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chen" authorityYear="2007" box="[554,636,1215,1239]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Cacoxenus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gani">
<emphasis box="[554,573,1215,1239]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[589,636,1215,1239]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">gani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not referred to in the following description.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[138,1185,1278,1334]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">
<emphasis box="[138,206,1278,1302]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Head.</emphasis>
Ocellar triangle brown, with three pairs of small setae above ocellar setae. Frontal vitta, pedicel, first flagellomere, gene, and postgena brown. Occiput brown-black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[138,1185,1374,1462]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">
<emphasis box="[138,226,1374,1398]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Thorax.</emphasis>
Obscure brown, with brown-black patches, grey pollinose pattern, and dark clouds around sockets of setae. Postpronotal lobe with a long humeral seta and seven or eight small setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[138,462,1502,1526]" box="[138,462,1502,1526]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">
<emphasis box="[138,195,1502,1525]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Legs.</emphasis>
Yellow, partly brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[138,1185,1565,1685]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">
<emphasis box="[138,320,1565,1589]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Male terminalia.</emphasis>
Epandrium pubescent dorsally, with about 11 setae near posterior margin; anteroventral corners protruding (
<figureCitation box="[550,650,1597,1621]" captionStart="Figures 8–11" captionStartId="5.[138,207,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[142,1182,137,871]" captionTargetId="figure-146@5.[138,1186,133,875]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 8–11. Cacoxenus (Nankangomyia) unipaxillus sp. nov., „. (8) Antenna. (9) Epandrium, cercus, and surstylus, lateral view. (10, 11) Hypandrium (hypd), gonopod (gon), parameres (pm), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a), ventral and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233486/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Figure 9</figureCitation>
). Parameres slightly sclerotized, with ca 17 sensilla arranged longitudinally, basally articulated with tip of lateral arm of aedeagal apodeme (
<figureCitation box="[260,431,1661,1685]" captionStart="Figures 8–11" captionStartId="5.[138,207,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[142,1182,137,871]" captionTargetId="figure-146@5.[138,1186,133,875]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 8–11. Cacoxenus (Nankangomyia) unipaxillus sp. nov., „. (8) Antenna. (9) Epandrium, cercus, and surstylus, lateral view. (10, 11) Hypandrium (hypd), gonopod (gon), parameres (pm), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a), ventral and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233486/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Figures 10, 11</figureCitation>
). Vertical lobe of gonopod slightly sclerotized (
<figureCitation box="[985,1099,1661,1685]" captionStart="Figures 8–11" captionStartId="5.[138,207,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[142,1182,137,871]" captionTargetId="figure-146@5.[138,1186,133,875]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 8–11. Cacoxenus (Nankangomyia) unipaxillus sp. nov., „. (8) Antenna. (9) Epandrium, cercus, and surstylus, lateral view. (10, 11) Hypandrium (hypd), gonopod (gon), parameres (pm), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a), ventral and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233486/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2705">Figure 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
